Incident Response > [T3]: Lab - Suricata (Network Level Detection)

What is Suricata?


Suricata is an open-source NSM (Network Security Monitoring) that can analyze live traffic and PCAP files. 

By default, it works as an IDS (Intrusion Detection System) to monitor network traffic. It can also work as an IPS (Intrusion Prevention System) and block traffic based on matched signatures. 

Suricata can be installed on a single machine or on a GW (Gateway) to inspect inbound and outbound traffic and alert.

 

What will we learn in this lab?

  1. Overview of Suricata settings and logs
  2. Analyze a PCAP and match it against Suricata signatures (Backdoor:Win32/Pushdo.A)
  3. Detect malicious traffic using Suricata as an IDS (Nmap)
  4. Write a custom signature to alert on traffic (Alert based on the HTTP Host Header)

 

Please, replace cyberdefenders.org with 45.33.32.156 (in the given examples).

 

Overview of Suricata settings and logs

Suricata's config file is located under /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml, and it is a YAML file with all the parameters to run Suricata. So, to test Suricata's settings, go ahead and execute the following: 

sudo suricata -T /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml


The command might take some time to finish, but you should see a message like this one (when it ends): 

<Notice> - Configuration provided was successfully loaded. Exiting.

Suricata creates five default log files under the /var/log/suricata directory:

  • suricata.log & suricata-start.log: Log messages of Suricata itself.
  • stats.log: Statistics records on a fixed interval, by default, every 8 seconds.
  • fast.log: Suspicious traffic found by Suricata.
  • eve.json: Both detailed traffic and fast logs in JSON format.
